**BAM—classic React "Cannot read property 'map' of undefined" fix. Do this NOW (5 mins max):**

## **QUICK PATCH (Copy-paste these):**

```jsx
// ❌ BROKEN (what you probably have)
{data.map(item => <div>{item.name}</div>)}

// ✅ FIXED - Add these 3 guards
{data && Array.isArray(data) && data.length > 0 ? (
  data.map(item => <div>{item.name}</div>)
) : (
  <div>Loading...</div> // or whatever fallback
)}
```

**OR** even shorter (one-liner):
```jsx
{(data || []).map(item => <div>{item.name}</div>)}
```

## **ROOT CAUSE (99% of cases):**
- API call hasn't finished → `data` is `undefined`
- Prop not passed from parent
- State init wrong

## **2-MINUTE DEBUG:**
1. Console.log your data **right before** the `.map()`:
```jsx
console.log('DATA:', data); // What's it actually undefined?
```
2. Check your `useEffect`/`useState`:
```jsx
const [data, setData] = useState([]); // <- MUST be [] not null/undefined
```

## **NUKE IT FROM ORBIT (if desperate):**
```jsx
// Replace your entire map block with this bulletproof version
<div>
  {(() => {
    if (!data) return <div>Loading...</div>;
    if (!Array.isArray(data)) return <div>No data</div>;
    return data.map((item, index) => (
      <div key={item.id || index}>{item.name}</div>
    ));
  })()}
</div>
```

**Paste the fixed version, refresh, done.** Your demo will work perfectly. 

